article.description:
Chris Webber led eight Kings in double
figures with 16 points and 14 rebounds as Sacramento added another
remarkable chapter to the best season in franchise history, beating
the New York Knicks 116-82 Sunday night.
article.headline: Kings set franchise mark with 34th home victory
article.linkText: Webber, Kings hand Knicks worst loss of year
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- If it's any consolation to the New York Knicks, even coach Rick Adelman had never seen the Sacramento Kings play any better.
“ Once we get that knack going, everything just seems to click. We knew we owed them because of that win they got against us in New York. We thought it was going to be a good, tough game. Obviously, it wasn't. ”
— Kings guard Bobby Jackson
Chris Webber led eight Kings in double figures with 16 points, 14 rebounds and seven assists as Sacramento added another remarkable chapter to the best season in franchise history, beating the Knicks 116-82 Sunday night. The NBA-leading Kings (57-19) returned from a perfect six-game road trip to humiliate the last-place Knicks with another dazzling display of ball movement and shooting. By the time it was over, even Adelman was amazed -- and New York coach Don Chaney was wishing he had somebody to hit. "It was unbelievable," Adelman said with a shake of his head. "Sometimes we were hitting the third or fourth option, and it just kept happening all night long. That was about as good as I've seen us." Vlade Divac had 14 points and eight rebounds, while Peja Stojakovic had 13 points in his second game back from a nine-game absence with a hamstring injury. Everyone in a white-and-purple uniform seemingly had a highlight, from Bobby Jackson's stirring three-point play to Doug Christie's thunderous dunk to Hedo Turkoglu's 3-pointer at the first-half buzzer. In its eighth straight victory, Sacramento outscored New York 36-12 in the second quarter, stretched the lead to 43 points in the third and coasted through the final 14 minutes with five reserves on the court. "Once we get that knack going, everything just seems to click," said Jackson, who scored 15 points. "We knew we owed them because of that win they got against us in New York. We thought it was going to be a good, tough game. Obviously, it wasn't." Latrell Sprewell scored 19 points for the Knicks, who lost for the fourth time in six games. At 29-47, the lottery-bound Knicks are closing in on their worst season since 1986-87 -- the last time New York missed the playoffs. As the rout wore on, Sprewell resorted to wild shots on several possessions as the Knicks struggled even to get open. He and Christie got double technical fouls for a shouting match after Sprewell elbowed Christie in the head, then shoved him on the next possession. "It just got to the point with me where I got frustrated," Sprewell said. "When you're going to let guys push you around, stuff happens. It's about showing people that we're not going to roll over. We needed to start a fight, that was the point I was trying to make." The Kings improved the NBA's best home record and set a franchise record with their 34th home victory. Arco Arena's fans wore themselves out giving standing ovations as every starter left the court in the second half. "We were very flat and not aggressive, and they were very aggressive and very sharp," Chaney said. "I admire the way (Sprewell) was aggressive (against Christie). I might have hit somebody myself." With a 3½-game lead over the Lakers (54-23) and a game in hand, Sacramento's magic number is three for the franchise's first division title since moving to Northern California in 1985. It would be the first banner of any kind in Arco Arena representing team success for the Kings. The franchise, which began as the Rochester Royals in 1948, has won just four division titles -- and just one since 1952. Led by Otis Birdsong and Scott Wedman, the Kansas City Kings won the Midwest in 1978-79. It was embarrassing, but it wasn't the worst loss of the season for the Knicks, who committed 23 turnovers and shot less than 35 percent for most of the night. Charlotte won 111-68 at Madison Square Garden earlier this season. "We didn't do much of anything well," said Allan Houston, who had 18 points and a career-high 12 rebounds. "We came into a place where we were meeting the No. 1 team. You have to play the perfect game." Webber had eight points, six rebounds and five assists in the first quarter alone. Sacramento made a 17-4 run in the second quarter, followed quickly by a 13-2 run. New York managed one field goal in the final 5:10 of the first half, which ended on Turkoglu's roof-raising 3-pointer from the corner. Chaney rarely left his seat on the bench in the second half, but he left Sprewell and Houston on the floor for the entire fourth quarter. Game notes
Christie had 10 points, eight assists and six steals before fouling out midway through the third quarter. "I thought he was probably going to foul out anyway, so I just decided to let him go," Adelman said with a shrug. ... New York hasn't won in Sacramento since 1997. ... The game was originally scheduled to be broadcast nationally, but NBC chose the Lakers-Heat game instead. ... Celebrity sightings, Sacramento style: In the front row, former teen actor Mario Lopez and Doritos commercial girl Ali Landry sat three seats down from TV personality Robin Leach.
